{"title_page": "David Boyd Haycock", "text_new": "'''David Boyd Haycock''' (born 1968 in [[Banbury]], [[Oxfordshire]])<ref>{{cite web|title=About me|url=http://www.davidboydhaycock.co.uk/about_me/index.php|publisher=David Boyd Haycock|accessdate=31 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716182405/http://www.davidboydhaycock.co.uk/about_me/index.php|archive-date=16 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> is a British writer, curator and lecturer. He read 'Modern History' at [[St John's College, Oxford]], and has an MA in the History of Art from the University of Sussex and a PhD in History from [[Birkbeck College, London]]. He is the author of a number of books, including ''William Stukeley: Science, Archaeology and Religion in Eighteenth Century England'' (2002) ''Paul Nash'' (2002, 2nd edition 2016),<ref>{{cite book|last=Haycock|first=David Boyd|title=Paul Nash|year=2002|publisher=[[Tate Publishing Ltd|Tate Publishing]]|isbn=1-85437-436-2|oclc=50176269}}</ref> ''Mortal Coil: A Short History of Living Longer'' (2008)<ref>{{cite news|last=Purves|first=Libby|authorlink=Libby Purves|title=Mortal Coil by David Boyd Haycock and Not Dead Yet by Julia Neuberger|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/non-fiction/article4079548.ece|work=[[Times Online]]|date=6 June 2008|accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> and ''A Crisis of Brilliance: Five Young British Artists and the Great War'' (2009), a group biography of the artists [[Paul Nash (artist)|Paul Nash]], [[Stanley Spencer]], [[Mark Gertler (artist)|Mark Gertler]], [[Dora Carrington]] and [[C.R.W. Nevinson]], all of whom were students together at the [[Slade School of Art]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|last=Uglow|first=Jenny|authorlink=Jenny Uglow|title=A Crisis of Brilliance: Five Young British Artists and the Great War by David Boyd Haycock|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/nov/21/brilliance-artists-david-haycock-review|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 November 2009|accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> He lives in Oxford.<ref name=oxfordtimes/>\n\n''A Crisis of Brilliance'' was nominated in the \"Best Non-Fiction Book\" category at the 2010 [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] awards.<ref name=oxfordtimes>{{cite news|last=Hartford|first=Maggie|title=Double delight for author David|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/8470974.Double_delight_for_author_David/|work=[[Oxford Times]]|date=23 October 2010|accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> An exhibition based on the book was held at [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]] in the summer of 2013. His most recent book was ''I Am Spain: The Spanish Civil War and the Men and Women who went to Fight Fascism'' (2012).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.davidboydhaycock.co.uk/}}\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2001-153875}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haycock, David Boyd}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Banbury]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''David Boyd Haycock''' (born 1968 in [[Banbury]], [[Oxfordshire]])<ref>{{cite web|title=About me|url=http://www.davidboydhaycock.co.uk/about_me/index.php|publisher=David Boyd Haycock|accessdate=31 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716182405/http://www.davidboydhaycock.co.uk/about_me/index.php|archive-date=16 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> is a British writer, curator and lecturer. He read 'Modern History' at [[St John's College, Oxford]], and has an MA in the History of Art from the University of Sussex and a PhD in History from [[Birkbeck College, London]]. He is the author of a number of books, including ''William Stukeley: Science, Archaeology and Religion in Eighteenth Century England'' (2002) ''Paul Nash'' (2002, 2nd edition 2016),<ref>{{cite book|last=Haycock|first=David Boyd|title=Paul Nash|year=2002|publisher=[[Tate Publishing Ltd|Tate Publishing]]|isbn=1-85437-436-2|oclc=50176269}}</ref>, ''Mortal Coil: A Short History of Living Longer'' (2008)<ref>{{cite news|last=Purves|first=Libby|authorlink=Libby Purves|title=Mortal Coil by David Boyd Haycock and Not Dead Yet by Julia Neuberger|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/non-fiction/article4079548.ece|work=[[Times Online]]|date=6 June 2008|accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> and ''A Crisis of Brilliance: Five Young British Artists and the Great War'' (2009), a group biography of the artists [[Paul Nash (artist)|Paul Nash]], [[Stanley Spencer]], [[Mark Gertler (artist)|Mark Gertler]], [[Dora Carrington]] and [[C.R.W. Nevinson]], all of whom were students together at the [[Slade School of Art]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|last=Uglow|first=Jenny|authorlink=Jenny Uglow|title=A Crisis of Brilliance: Five Young British Artists and the Great War by David Boyd Haycock|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/nov/21/brilliance-artists-david-haycock-review|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 November 2009|accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> He lives in Oxford.<ref name=oxfordtimes/>\n\n''A Crisis of Brilliance'' was nominated in the \"Best Non-Fiction Book\" category at the 2010 [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] awards.<ref name=oxfordtimes>{{cite news|last=Hartford|first=Maggie|title=Double delight for author David|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/8470974.Double_delight_for_author_David/|work=[[Oxford Times]]|date=23 October 2010|accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> An exhibition based on the book was held at [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]] in the summer of 2013. His most recent book was ''I Am Spain: The Spanish Civil War and the Men and Women who went to Fight Fascism'' (2012).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.davidboydhaycock.co.uk/}}\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2001-153875}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haycock, David Boyd}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[